We got our adult (Staffy/Pitbull/mix?) dog from a shelter and he came with some health issues. He had dry, flaky greasy skin, a dull coat, very soft, sometimes diarrhea, stool,  a strong body odor, hot spots and severe itching during the summer into fall months. He also had warts and bare skin on his elbows. After almost 4 years of experimenting with different good quality kibble and various supplements , most of those issues are resolved or greatly reduced. He is now on Merrick kibble (beef), Hyperbiotics probiotic, Dasuquin and SeaMeal. I tried him on a Missing Link supplement but think the SeaMeal is better. With SeaMeal, his body order is not strong at all and he seems to shed less fur. Now, his coat is good, his stool is normal with a predictable schedule and even his body warts have either disappeared or been reduced in size. The seasonal itching is still present but much better, especially if we catch it early.
If your dog has some health issues, be patient trying new things. Only change one thing at a time and introduce it slowly. Try it for at least a month.
summary: definitely worth a try for odor and shedding

Firstly, I'm a former vet tech and I can tell you that if you are having a really severe, active flea infestation, this probably isn't the best option for you.  You're better off getting a name brand, prescription product for your cats (Revolution, Bravecto or Comfortis are all good) and doing a multistep approach of house treatments, flea baths, and meds. Frontline was one of the first products to be introduced to the market and fleas have been exposed to it more than most other products, meaning they have built up a tolerance.  Flea meds effectiveness varies depending on the area you live. This product is basically a generic of Frontline (same active ingredient).  If Frontline doesn't work for you, this product won't either.

I've been using this on my indoor only cats as a preventative and so far it works great!  I have two indoor cats and two indoor/outdoor dogs.  One of my cats has a really severe flea allergy that will land her at the vet if she gets bit by even one flea.  Using prescription meds on my dogs and over the counter stuff on my cats (who are less likely to encounter fleas) seems to be the trick.  This is priced MUCH lower than Frontline (which runs about 4X as much as the Sentry brand generic), which is awesome.  It's also packaged nicely and seems to be more concentrated than Frontline so I don't' end up dumping a bunch of liquid on my cats, who aren't excited about flea med time anyway.

This bowl may literally be a life saver! If you have a pooch who wolfs their food down, they may be susceptible to bloat. I lost a dog to that condition--he died overnight with very little warning. Our vet said that he has seen bloat kill a dog in half an hour.

We currently have 2 German Shorthairs [who could care less about meals] and a Plott Hound. The Plott is super food oriented, as is typical of the breed. Think of Labrador on meth! Before using this bowl, he would consume all of his food quickly and then bully the other two dogs away from their bowls. Sometimes I would feed him outside, but I have better things to do than babysit dogs at mealtime.

After the second time of losing his dinner on the living room carpet I decided to get the large Teal bowl. This has been the BEST purchase! Now "Ollie" is the last to finish his food--by a long shot. Being a hound, I think that he actually enjoys the "chase" of getting his food from this feeder. Although an intelligent breed, he has yet to figure out that he could still go bully the other dogs for their food. Again, I believe that the challenge of getting the food from the nooks and crannies of the Slow Feeder is engaging for him. He has slimmed down a few pound too--because he is consuming less.

The feeder is pretty easy to clean. I use a bottle brush and a little dish soap. The description says that you can wash it in the dishwasher, but I only do a load every 2 or 3 days, and I feed the dogs 2X per day.

Most importantly, feeding the Plott this way substantially reduces his possibility of experiencing bloat. It could well extend his life. If you have a dog who eats quickly, this bowl is insurance!

PS--although I prefer stainless steel--and there are some slow feeders available in SS, I wanted the tighter pattern of this bowl. It has been perfect.

Beautiful, lush green. This plant is so pretty and such a visual statement piece in the aquarium that  I wish I had more tanks for it!

Each pot contained three plants.  I divided them into two aquariums where they have been planted for a week now. There is some melt and the loss of a leaf or two in the 40g, which is to be expected as they adjust to each aquarium's unique ecology, different to the grower's set up they had known. I have some regular val in the same tank and it melted away almost completely when first introduced, then grew back vigorously, so I expect similar for the new arrivals, especially as the newly shipped roots are so short.

Two of them had really short roots, about 1/4 inch, so they kept popping up. I had to resort to a tiny dab of Superglue to attach the escapees to an obliging small rock so the roots could nestle down into the substrate. The others had roots of about 3/8 to 1/2 inch so they did stay down, barely.  I need to be careful not to jostle them or make too much current nearby when doing maintenance as the leaves are extra fragile while they semi soften due to change in water parameters and until they establish a deeper root system.
Note:  Greenpro advised planting into substrate as soon as possible and not to just put it into the tank still in the pot. Apparently leaving the roots in rock wool puts them at risk of rot?

The first one I ordered arrived damaged as the rock wool root ball had popped loose from the plastic pot in transit and slammed around in the package, bruising and cracking the leaves beyond hope. I sent pics and Greenpro customer service was top notch, sending a replacement which I was able to piggy-back onto a second order. Successful shipping the second time around, all the way from CA to the east coast in May with temps in the high 70's, very low 80's F.

Two of them are planted in a 40g breeder tank which is 2/3 Walstad style and one third beach. The v. spiralis are in the beach area which has a one inch substrate of pool sand, sieved through a fine mesh sieve so that only the larger grains were retained and used (to increase beach aeration). Beneath the sand where the vals go there is some added Eco Complete substrate, a teaspoon of ground baked eggshells to add minerals, and a small blob of low fire red terra cotta clay to add iron.
The others are individually replanted, dirted Walstad style, in glass pots and are in a 29 gallon cycled holding tank.

Love them.
summary: Gorgeous plant, great customer service from Greenpro
